ergo animus qui: many editors (Or. Hei. etc.) omit qui, but there seems to be no satisfactory theory to account for its presence except the view of Sff. (adopted by Schiche) who holds that qui arose out of quidem, the animus quidem or ipse animus being finished with here and the question ofits sedes and forma being taken up in §67. The choice seems to lie between this and the view of Kuh. who retains qui, observing ‘Ipsi Ciceroni uitium orationis tribuendum puto 3 uidetur enim primun] orationem sic conformaturus fuisse: ergo animus, qui, ut ego dico, diuinus est, ut Euripides dicere audet, deus, si deus aut anima aut ignis est, idem est (h.e. aut anima aut ignis est); deinde autem inchoatam structuram mu- tauit, quo maiore ui animum hominis efferret.¹

For the sentiment cf. Rep. vi 24 ‘mens cuiusque is est quisque...si quidem deus est qui uiget, qui sentit, qui meminit, qui prouidet‚ qui tam regit et moderatur et mouet id corpuS, cui praepositus est, quam hunc mundum ille princeps deus'; also Off. iii 10, 44 ‘deun]...id est, ut ego arbitror, mentem suam, qua nihil hornini dedit deus ipse diuinius.’
